results.title: Manchester Population Density-Copy
results.description:
Census data reveals that population density varies noticeably from area to area. Small area census data do a better job depicting how where the crowded neighborhoods are. 

In this map, the yellow areas of highest density range from 30,000 to 150,000 persons per square kilometer. In those areas, if the people were spread out evenly across the area, there would be just 4 to 9 meters between them. Very high density areas exceed 7,000 persons per square kilometer. High density areas exceed 5,200 persons per square kilometer. The last categories break at 3,330 persons per square kilometer, and 1,500 persons per square kilometer. 

This map was created using Census 2011 data combined with Ordnance Survey's Open Boundaries and Ordnance Survey Open Map Local's Buildings layer.

How to make this map for your city

results.title: UPRN PoC Web Map Greater Manchester v1.1
results.description:
This Web Map contains datasets from multiple data providers, such as Ordnance Survey (OS), United Kingdom Centre for Ecology & Hydrology (UKCEH), Department for Environment, Food & Rural Affairs (DEFRA), Met Office, etc. to provide a proof-of-concept solution for a service that enables streamlined access to government geospatial data through querying on the Unique Property Reference Number (UPRN) level. Users are able to select UPRNs and access the values from the underlying datasets.

The service contains the following data groups:
  • UPRN points
  • Administrative areas
  • Environmental variables from the ClimateJust project
  • Noise pollution data from DEFRA
  • Modelled background pollution data from DEFRA
  • Carbon storage and water supply data from UKCEH
  • Ellenberg Vegetation Indicator data from UKCEH
  • Multiple datasets from Met Office's Air Quality Reanalysis datasets
The above datasets, combined with Ordnance Survey's most up-to-date UPRN register, comprise the basis of an efficient workflow for acquiring localised pollution, vegetation, and administrative information. This, in turn, provides decision makers with enhanced and granular understanding of the connection of different phenomena, resulting in more informed actions on any scale from national to local.
results.snippet: Web Map containing the Proof of Concept Unique Property Reference Number (UPRN) Service for Greater Manchester. It integrates and presents data from several agencies in an easily queriable way, enabling users to access environmental and administrative information on the UPRN level.

results.title: Carbon Storage Web Map (Greater Manchester)
results.description: This data set contains UK-wide maps of ten different among-model ensemble approaches for two services: above ground Carbon stock and water supply. The data for Carbon comes as fourteen TIF maps for above ground carbon storage at a 1-km2 resolution with associated world files: ten approaches, with a double option for two of those, together with maps of variation among models and among ensembles. For water, the data comes as one shapefile with polygons per watershed, each polygon containing these fourteen estimates. For all maps, 600dpi jpg depictions are added to the supporting information. Directory location independent layer files are included to aid scaling and providing the colour palettes. Ensemble output maps were calculated with different approaches following the supporting documentation and associated publication. Uncertainty estimates for these services are included as variation among contributing model outputs and among the employed ensemble approaches. The work was completed under the ‘EnsemblES - Using ensemble techniques to capture the accuracy and sensitivity of ecosystem service models’ project (NE/T00391X/1) funded by the UKRI Landscape Decisions programme. Full details about this dataset can be found at https://doi.org/10.5285/a9ae773d-b742-4d42-ae42-2b594bae5d38
results.snippet: Carbon Storage Web Map (Greater Manchester)

results.title: Public Transport Accessibility, Household Vehicle Accessibility, and Unemployment - Greater Manchester
results.description: The links between personal mobility and employment has long been an area of concern across Transport Geography and Planning literature, often informing transport policy (Johnson et al., 2017). To this end, it is helpful to understand the spatiality of different transport and employment needs – Are there areas of high employment and low car ownership centred around public transit? Or areas of transport exclusion with high unemployment? This map, therefore, aims to communicate the relationship between public transport (PT) accessibility, household vehicle access, and employment across Greater Manchester.
results.snippet: Mapping the relationship between public transport accessibility, household vehicle accessibility, and unemployment.

results.title: Brexit voting by region
results.description: In light of Brexit negotiations once again reaching a stalemate, I decided to map the relationship between disposable income and referendum results across the national scale. A bivariate choropleth map was used to illustrate the relationship. The expected outcome was that areas with low disposable incomes would have a lower percentage of remain votes whilst the opposite would be true for areas of high disposable income.
results.snippet: This map illustrates the relationship between disposable income and and results of the 2016 EU Referendum.

results.title: Political walking and the picturesque
results.description:
Through a range of picturesque and political walking data, this map explores different modes of engagement with The Peak District. Gilpin’s tour is presented as points as his emphasis is on picturesque vistas. Whereas the movement between Gilpin’s sites is negligible, the walking routes taken by the Trespassers and Black Girls Hike (BGH) is the substance of their engagement, people being in and moving through the land. BGH continues the trespasser’s legacy of political walking, building confidence in black women who may feel unwelcome in predominantly white middleclass outdoor spaces. In an interesting tension with the picturesque BGH also emphasises the visual: representing black women in the countryside so that others see this space as accessible. For BGH, the political power of people in the landscape is far from Gilpin’s aesthetic amorality. Similarly, pictures of the trespassers helped build support for the right to roam movement. The political walking shown combines experiential movement and visual representation, complicating a purely picturesque landscape. All three sources are about bringing people to The Peaks, whether that be picturesque tourism or rambling. The paradox of people engaging more with the landscape is that whilst it increases environmentalism it also increases risk of wildlife damage. The high frequency of wildfires on Kinder Scout demonstrates this increased engagement and increased risk. This landscape, with such a strong history of political walking, demonstrates that a new form of political, environmentally engaged, walking must emerge for the landscape’s posterity in the age of the climate crisis.

<o:p></o:p>
results.snippet: Through a range of picturesque and political walking data, this map explores different modes of engagement with The Peak District.

results.description: This dataset contains gridded Surface Level Bias Corrected Daily Air Quality Index of Particulate Matter < 2.5 µm data for the Greater Manchester area, for 2003. The data is derived from the AQREAN (Air Quality Reanalysis) model, which combines an air quality forecast model system with observations of pollutants. The data covers the Greater Manchester at a horizontal resolution of 0.1 degree (approximately 10 km). Full details about this dataset can be found at https://storymaps.arcgis.com/stories/bad1f0f37372421eb777e307b71a28cd
